docs {
  ## GET /api/auth/verify
  
  **Description**  
  Verifies a user account using a token received via email.  
  This endpoint is typically called when the user clicks on the verification link in their inbox.
  
  ---
  
  ### Request
  
  - **Method:** `GET`
  - **Endpoint:** `/api/verify`
  - **Authentication:** Not required
  
  ---
  
  ### Query parameters
  
  | Parameter | Type   | Required | Description                 |
  |-----------|--------|----------|-----------------------------|
  | `token`   | string | Yes      | Verification token from email |
  
  Example:
  ```
  GET /api/verify?token=abcdef123456
  ```
  
  ---
  
  ### Successful response
  
  | Status | Description           |
  |--------|-----------------------|
  | 200    | HTML success message  |
  
  ```html
  <!DOCTYPE html>
  <html lang="en">
    <head><title>Verification</title></head>
    <body>
      <h1>Account verified successfully</h1>
    </body>
  </html>
  ```
  
  ---
  
  ### Error responses
  
  | Status | Message                                  | Condition                          |
  |--------|-------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------|
  | 400    | `Verification token missing` (HTML)       | `token` query parameter is missing |
  | 400    | `Invalid or expired token` (HTML)         | Token is not in DB or expired      |
  | 404    | `User not found` (HTML)                   | Token exists, but user ID does nicht |
  | 500    | `Verification failed due to server error` | DB/Server Fehler beim Update       |
  
  ---
  
  ### Notes
  
  - This endpoint returns an **HTML page**, not a JSON response.
  - The verification token is single-use and time-limited.
  - After success, the user can log in normally via `POST /api/login`.
  
}
